1074
01:45:59,480 --> 01:46:02,320
Not only what can be seen.. .

1075
01:46:02,480 --> 01:46:06,320
.. .but what ís takíng place ínsíde.

1076
01:46:06,480 --> 01:46:11,280
Each tíme ít has happened.
l feel l have a sweet secret.. .

1077
01:46:11,440 --> 01:46:18,040
...and l long for the tíme when l shall
feel that secret wíthín me agaín.

1078
01:48:05,560 --> 01:48:09,040
FRANK:
Annele! Peter!

1079
01:48:09,240 --> 01:48:12,960
A wonderful surprise,
Mr. Kraler and Miep are here.

1080
01:48:13,120 --> 01:48:15,240
Thank you. You shouldn't have come.

1081
01:48:15,440 --> 01:48:18,880
You should have
at least one day to yourselves.

1082
01:48:19,040 --> 01:48:21,880
ANNE: Don't say that.
It's so wonderful to see them.

1083
01:48:22,040 --> 01:48:24,680
-What is it? What is it?
ANNE: Mr. Kraler.

1084
01:48:24,840 --> 01:48:28,640
-Happy New Year, Mr. Dussel.
-Happy New Year.

1085
01:48:28,800 --> 01:48:30,960
How are you, Margot?
Feeling any better?

1086
01:48:31,120 --> 01:48:35,360
-l'm all right.
-We filled her full of every kind of pill...

1087
01:48:35,520 --> 01:48:37,600
...so she won't cough
and make a noise.

1088
01:48:37,760 --> 01:48:40,400
Look what Miep has brought us.

1089
01:48:40,560 --> 01:48:42,840
A cake!

1090
01:48:43,000 --> 01:48:44,400
ALL:
Ooh.

1091
01:48:44,880 --> 01:48:47,360
-A cake.
-Well.

1092
01:48:48,240 --> 01:48:50,160
l'll get some plates.

1093
01:48:50,320 --> 01:48:52,200
-Thank you, Miep.
-Thank you.

1094
01:48:52,920 --> 01:48:55,920
You must have used all
of your sugar rations for weeks.

1095
01:48:56,080 --> 01:48:58,920
lt's beautiful, isn't it?

1096
01:48:59,080 --> 01:49:01,320
lt's ages since l've even seen a cake.

1097
01:49:01,480 --> 01:49:04,160
Not since you brought the one last year.
Remember?

1098
01:49:04,320 --> 01:49:08,240
lt had ''Peace in 1 943'' written on it.

1099
01:49:10,880 --> 01:49:13,000
''Peace in 1 944.''

1100
01:49:14,720 --> 01:49:16,640
Peace has to come sometime,
you know.

1101
01:49:18,360 --> 01:49:20,560
Here you are, líef_e.

1102
01:49:20,720 --> 01:49:22,480
Now...

1103
01:49:22,640 --> 01:49:24,960
-...how many of us are there?
MIEP: None for me.

1104
01:49:25,160 --> 01:49:26,760
-Oh, you must.
-Please, Miep.

1105
01:49:26,920 --> 01:49:30,720
Good. That leaves one, two, three....

1106
01:49:30,880 --> 01:49:33,920
-Seven of us.
-Eight.

1107
01:49:34,080 --> 01:49:35,960
The same as it always is.

1108
01:49:36,120 --> 01:49:39,280
l left Margot out.
l take it for granted Margot won't eat.

1109
01:49:39,440 --> 01:49:41,960
-Why wouldn't she?
-l think it won't harm her.

1110
01:49:42,120 --> 01:49:47,120
All right, all right. l just didn't want her
to start coughing again, that's all.

1111
01:49:47,280 --> 01:49:51,440
And please,
Mrs. Frank should cut the cake.

1112
01:49:51,600 --> 01:49:53,440
What do you mean?

1113
01:49:53,600 --> 01:49:56,960
Well, Mrs. Frank divides things better.

1114
01:49:57,120 --> 01:50:01,400
-Just what are you trying to say?
-Forget it, we're wasting time.

1115
01:50:01,560 --> 01:50:04,280
Don't l always give everybody
exactly the same?

1116
01:50:07,600 --> 01:50:09,280
-Don't l?
-Forget it.

1117
01:50:09,440 --> 01:50:15,000
-No, l want an answer. Don't l?
-Yes, yes, yes.

1118
01:50:15,160 --> 01:50:18,200
Everybody gets exactly the same.. .

1119
01:50:18,360 --> 01:50:20,880
...except Mr. Van Daan gets
a little bit more.

1120
01:50:21,040 --> 01:50:23,200
That's a lie!
She always cuts the same--

1121
01:50:23,360 --> 01:50:25,360
Mr. Van Daan, please.

1122
01:50:25,520 --> 01:50:30,520
You see, Miep, what a little sugar cake
does to us? It goes right to our heads.

1123
01:50:31,200 --> 01:50:36,160
-Here you are, Mrs. Frank.
-Thank you.

1124
01:50:43,320 --> 01:50:47,840
-You're sure you won't have any?
KRALER: Very sure.

1125
01:50:48,480 --> 01:50:52,160
-Miep.
-No, thank you, really.

1126
01:50:52,960 --> 01:50:55,160
Cut the cake.

1127
01:51:16,720 --> 01:51:18,880
Thank you.

1128
01:51:23,120 --> 01:51:25,320
EDITH :
That's yours, Peter.

1129
01:51:28,040 --> 01:51:30,120
Maybe Mouschi went back
to our house.

1130
01:51:30,560 --> 01:51:33,560
You ever get over there?
Do you think that you could?

1131
01:51:33,760 --> 01:51:36,640
l'm afraid with him gone a week,
Peter....

1132
01:51:36,800 --> 01:51:42,640
Make up your mind. Already someone
has had a big nice meal from that cat.

1133
01:51:48,640 --> 01:51:51,480
-lt's delicious, Miep.
-Delicious.

1134
01:51:59,240 --> 01:52:02,880
Well, l must run.
There's a party tonight.

1135
01:52:03,040 --> 01:52:04,800
How heavenly!

1136
01:52:04,960 --> 01:52:07,040
Remember what everyone's wearing.. .

1137
01:52:07,240 --> 01:52:10,280
...and what you eat and everything
so you can tell us.

1138
01:52:10,480 --> 01:52:11,960
MIEP:
l'll give you a full report.

1139
01:52:12,160 --> 01:52:15,080
-Goodbye, everyone.
FRANK: Goodbye, Miep.

1140
01:52:15,240 --> 01:52:18,960
Just a minute. There's something l'd
like you to do for me.

1141
01:52:19,120 --> 01:52:21,480
PETRONELLA:
Where are you going?

1142
01:52:21,640 --> 01:52:24,440
What are you going to do?

1143
01:52:28,000 --> 01:52:30,080
No. Don't you dare take that coat.

1144
01:52:30,280 --> 01:52:34,960
-What is wrong?
PETER: Father is going to sell her fur coat.

1145
01:52:35,120 --> 01:52:38,480
-She's crazy about that old fur coat.
-lt's mine, you hear me?

1146
01:52:38,640 --> 01:52:42,560
My father gave me that coat.
No! You have no right!

1147
01:52:42,760 --> 01:52:45,840
ls it possible that anyone can...

1148
01:52:46,000 --> 01:52:50,000
...be silly enough to worry about
a fur coat at a time like this?

1149
01:52:50,320 --> 01:52:52,160
PETER:
It's none of your darn business.

1150
01:52:52,320 --> 01:52:56,200
-And if you say one more thing--
FRANK: Peter.

1151
01:53:01,680 --> 01:53:03,720
Just...

1152
01:53:03,920 --> 01:53:08,040
...a little discussion on the advisability
of selling this coat.

1153
01:53:08,200 --> 01:53:10,600
As l have often
reminded Mrs. Van Daan...

1154
01:53:10,840 --> 01:53:13,840
...it's selfish of her to keep it
when people outside...

1155
01:53:14,000 --> 01:53:16,440
...are in desperate need of clothing.

1156
01:53:16,640 --> 01:53:18,560
So if you please, sell it for us?

1157
01:53:18,720 --> 01:53:21,920
lt should fetch a good price.
And by the way...

1158
01:53:22,080 --> 01:53:26,560
...would you get me cigarettes?
l don't care what kind, get all you can.

1159
01:53:26,720 --> 01:53:31,920
lt is very difficult to get them,
Mr. Van Daan, but l'll try.

1160
01:53:32,080 --> 01:53:34,440
-Goodbye.
-Goodbye.

1161
01:53:34,600 --> 01:53:37,840
Mr. Frank, could l talk to you?

1162
01:53:42,280 --> 01:53:45,600
Something's happened, hasn't it,
Mr. Kraler? What's happened?

1163
01:53:45,760 --> 01:53:48,960
lf it is something that concerns us
here, we'd better all hear it.

1164
01:53:49,120 --> 01:53:50,840
-The children--
-What they'd imagine.. .

1165
01:53:51,000 --> 01:53:53,160
...would be worse than any reality.

1166
01:53:53,320 --> 01:53:56,320
lt is a man in the storeroom.
His name is Karl.

1167
01:53:56,480 --> 01:53:59,320
You knew him.
One day, he came to the office.

1168
01:53:59,520 --> 01:54:01,160
He closed the door and asked:

1169
01:54:01,320 --> 01:54:04,000
''What do you hear
from your friend Mr. Frank?''

1170
01:54:04,200 --> 01:54:06,800
l said there's a rumor
you were in Switzerland.

1171
01:54:06,960 --> 01:54:11,000
He said he had heard that rumor too,
but he thought l knew something more.

1172
01:54:11,240 --> 01:54:14,160
l did not pay much attention.
l tried to forget it.

1173
01:54:14,680 --> 01:54:20,440
And then yesterday, we were coming
out of the storeroom, out there.

1174
01:54:20,600 --> 01:54:24,040
l had started down to the office.

1175
01:54:24,200 --> 01:54:25,920
l looked back.

1176
01:54:26,080 --> 01:54:29,640
He was standing,
staring at the bookcase.

1177
01:54:29,840 --> 01:54:33,720
He said, ''l thought l remembered
a door up here.

1178
01:54:33,880 --> 01:54:38,200
Was not there a door code(0125)ere leading
to the loft?

1179
01:54:38,360 --> 01:54:40,600
Then he asked me for more money.

1180
01:54:40,760 --> 01:54:42,800
-20 guilders more a week.
-Blackmail.

1181
01:54:42,960 --> 01:54:48,040
-20 guilders? Very modest blackmail.
-That's just the beginning.

1182
01:54:48,960 --> 01:54:51,040
You know what l think?

1183
01:54:51,240 --> 01:54:54,600
He's the thief who
was down there that night.

1184
01:54:54,760 --> 01:54:56,760
That's how he knows we're here.

1185
01:54:56,920 --> 01:54:59,320
How was it left?
What did you tell him?

1186
01:54:59,480 --> 01:55:01,920
l told him l had to think about it.

1187
01:55:02,120 --> 01:55:06,120
What shall l do, pay him the money?
Take a chance on firing him, or what?

1188
01:55:06,280 --> 01:55:09,040
-l do not know.
-For heaven sakes, don't fire him.

1189
01:55:09,200 --> 01:55:10,520
Pay him what he asks.

1190
01:55:10,680 --> 01:55:13,360
Keep him here,
where you can keep your eye on him.

1191
01:55:13,520 --> 01:55:16,720
ls it much that he's asking?
What are they paying nowadays?

1192
01:55:16,880 --> 01:55:20,360
He could get it in a war plant.
But this is not a war plant.

1193
01:55:20,560 --> 01:55:24,960
Mind you,
l do not know if he knows or not.

1194
01:55:27,680 --> 01:55:31,080
Offer him half, then we'll soon know
if it is blackmail or not.

1195
01:55:31,280 --> 01:55:35,120
And if it is?
We've got to pay, haven't we?

1196
01:55:35,320 --> 01:55:41,280
-Whatever he asks, we've got to pay.
-Let us decide when the time comes.

1197
01:55:41,440 --> 01:55:45,000
This may be all my imagination.
You get to a point, these days...

1198
01:55:45,160 --> 01:55:48,080
.. .where you suspect everyone
and everything.

1199
01:55:48,240 --> 01:55:51,040
[SIRENS WAILING]
[TELEPHONE RINGING]

1200
01:56:04,080 --> 01:56:09,400
What does that mean,
the telephone ringing on a holiday?

1201
01:56:11,520 --> 01:56:15,760
That's my wife. l told her l had
to go over some papers in my office...

1202
01:56:15,920 --> 01:56:19,200
...to call me here when she got out
of church. Goodbye.

1203
01:56:20,360 --> 01:56:22,440
Happy New Year.

1204
01:56:22,600 --> 01:56:25,080
-Goodbye.
-Goodbye, Mr. Kraler.

1205
01:56:27,640 --> 01:56:32,960
KRALER: l will offer him half, then.
FRANK: Thank you, Mr. Kraler.

1206
01:56:38,040 --> 01:56:40,400
DUSSEL:
You can thank your son for this.

1207
01:56:40,560 --> 01:56:44,320
Him and his damn cat!
That night, there.

1208
01:56:45,200 --> 01:56:50,480
l tell you,
it's just a question of time now.

1209
01:56:55,720 --> 01:56:59,520
Sometimes l wish the end would come,
whatever it is.

1210
01:57:00,160 --> 01:57:04,320
-Margot!
-At least we'd know where we were.

1211
01:57:04,480 --> 01:57:09,040
You should be ashamed of yourself,
talking that way.

1212
01:57:09,200 --> 01:57:12,000
Think how lucky we are.

1213
01:57:12,160 --> 01:57:16,640
Think of the thousands dying
in the war every day.

1214
01:57:16,840 --> 01:57:19,160
Think of the people
in concentration camps.

1215
01:57:19,320 --> 01:57:21,560
What's the good of that?

1216
01:57:21,800 --> 01:57:25,760
What's the good of thinking of misery
when you're already miserable?

1217
01:57:25,920 --> 01:57:28,200
That's stupid!

1218
01:57:28,360 --> 01:57:30,760
We're young,
Margot and Peter and l.

1219
01:57:30,920 --> 01:57:35,040
You grownups have had your chance.

1220
01:57:35,200 --> 01:57:40,480
But look at us. If we begin thinking
of all the horror in the world, we're lost.

1221
01:57:40,640 --> 01:57:44,240
We're trying to hold on to some kind
of ideals when everything--

1222
01:57:44,400 --> 01:57:48,640
ldeals, hope, everything
is being destroyed.

1223
01:57:49,560 --> 01:57:52,800
lt isn't our fault the world
is in such a mess.

1224
01:57:53,000 --> 01:57:56,000
-We weren't around when this started.
-You listen to me!

1225
01:57:56,200 --> 01:57:58,560
So don't try to take it out on us!

1226
01:58:08,080 --> 01:58:11,320
VAN DAAN:
She talks as if we started the war.

1227
01:58:12,760 --> 01:58:14,600
Did we start the war?

1228
01:58:24,440 --> 01:58:28,840
-You left this.
-Thanks.

1229
01:58:33,560 --> 01:58:35,600
l thought you were fine just now.

1230
01:58:35,880 --> 01:58:38,960
You know how to talk to them.
l can't think when l'm mad.

1231
01:58:40,080 --> 01:58:42,280
l say too much.

1232
01:58:42,800 --> 01:58:45,160
l hurt people's feelings.

1233
01:58:47,520 --> 01:58:49,680
l think you're just fine.

1234
01:59:00,520 --> 01:59:02,760
Thank you, Peter.

1235
01:59:09,120 --> 01:59:12,640
J
Dussel, what he said about Mouschi
about somebody eating him...

1236
01:59:12,800 --> 01:59:15,280
...all l could think is l wanted
to hit him.

1237
01:59:15,440 --> 01:59:17,440
That's what l used to do at school.

1238
01:59:17,600 --> 01:59:20,000
But here a fight starts,
l duck in my room.

1239
01:59:20,160 --> 01:59:23,240
You're lucky, having a room to go to.

1240
01:59:23,400 --> 01:59:26,280
His Lordship is always in mine.

1241
01:59:26,440 --> 01:59:30,240
When they start in on me,
l have to stand and take it.

1242
01:59:30,400 --> 01:59:33,480
You gave some of it back
to them just now.

1243
01:59:33,640 --> 01:59:36,440
l get so mad.

1244
01:59:36,600 --> 01:59:39,040
They've formed their opinions.. .

1245
01:59:39,200 --> 01:59:41,840
.. .about everything.

1246
01:59:42,000 --> 01:59:46,440
But we're still trying to find out.

1247
01:59:46,600 --> 01:59:52,080
We have problems here that
no other people our age have ever had.

1248
01:59:52,240 --> 01:59:54,640
And just as you
think you've solved them...

1249
01:59:54,800 --> 01:59:59,280
...something comes along and bang!

1250
01:59:59,440 --> 02:00:02,240
You have to start all over again.

1251
02:00:05,760 --> 02:00:10,360
-l think your father's fine.
-Oh, he is, Peter. He is.

1252
02:00:10,520 --> 02:00:15,480
He's the only one who's ever given me
the feeling that l have any sense.

1253
02:00:20,240 --> 02:00:23,560
lsn't it funny, you and l?

1254
02:00:23,720 --> 02:00:26,280
Here we've been together
all this time.. .

1255
02:00:26,440 --> 02:00:30,160
...and this is the first time we've
ever really talked.

1256
02:00:32,720 --> 02:00:37,080
lt helps a lot to have someone to talk to,
doesn't it?

1257
02:00:37,240 --> 02:00:40,480
lt helps you let off steam.

1258
02:00:57,080 --> 02:01:01,480
Anytime that you want
to let off steam...

1259
02:01:01,760 --> 02:01:03,840
...you can come into my room.

1260
02:01:05,480 --> 02:01:08,560
l can get up an awful lot of steam.

1261
02:01:08,720 --> 02:01:11,840
lt's all right with me.

1262
02:01:12,000 --> 02:01:14,200
Do you mean that?

1263
02:01:17,400 --> 02:01:20,480
l said it, didn't l?

1264
02:01:36,400 --> 02:01:39,560
-Good night.
-Good night.

1265
02:01:39,840 --> 02:01:41,760
Good night.

1266
02:01:52,040 --> 02:01:57,720
-May l come in?
ANNE: No, l'm not dressed yet.

1267
02:02:23,400 --> 02:02:25,280
Margot.

1268
02:02:25,480 --> 02:02:29,800
-Tell me, am l terribly ugly?
MARGOT: Oh, stop fishing.

1269
02:02:29,960 --> 02:02:31,600
No, tell me.

1270
02:02:31,760 --> 02:02:35,760
Of course you're not.
You've got nice eyes...

1271
02:02:35,920 --> 02:02:38,720
...and a lot of animation and....

1272
02:03:00,000 --> 02:03:03,000
-May l come in?
MARGOT: Come in, Mother.

1273
02:03:03,200 --> 02:03:08,560
EDITH: Mr. Dussel is impatient to get in.
ANNE: He takes the room all day.

1274
02:03:08,760 --> 02:03:12,240
You're not going in again tonight
to see Peter?

1275
02:03:12,400 --> 02:03:15,880
That is my intention.

1276
02:03:17,880 --> 02:03:21,000
Aren't you afraid
you're disturbing him?

1277
02:03:21,160 --> 02:03:23,320
Mother, l have some intuition.

1278
02:03:23,480 --> 02:03:29,400
Then may l ask this much, Annie?
Don't shut the door when you go in.

1279
02:03:31,000 --> 02:03:33,040
You sound like Mrs. Van Daan.

1280
02:03:33,200 --> 02:03:37,000
No, no. l don't mean
to suggest anything is wrong.

1281
02:03:37,200 --> 02:03:40,240
l only wish you wouldn't
expose yourself to criticism.

1282
02:03:40,440 --> 02:03:44,080
l'm sorry, Mother.
l'm going to Peter's room.

1283
02:03:44,240 --> 02:03:49,280
l'm not going to let Petronella Van Daan
spoil our friendship.

1284
02:03:54,040 --> 02:03:56,840
Just a moment, Mr. Dussel.

1285
02:03:59,240 --> 02:04:01,440
ln my day,
the boys called on the girls.

1286
02:04:01,640 --> 02:04:04,160
EDITH: You know how young people are.
Peter's room...

1287
02:04:04,320 --> 02:04:07,080
-...is the only place where they can talk.
-Talk?

1288
02:04:07,240 --> 02:04:09,920
That's not what they called it
when l was a girl.

1289
02:04:12,240 --> 02:04:16,360
l'm sorry, Margot,
that you have to be the one left out.

1290
02:04:18,040 --> 02:04:22,560
-l feel so guilty about you.
-Why?

1291
02:04:24,040 --> 02:04:29,440
l mean,
every time l go into Peter's room...

1292
02:04:29,600 --> 02:04:33,120
...l have the feeling
that l'm hurting you.

1293
02:04:33,360 --> 02:04:37,720
l know if it were me,
l'd be desperately jealous.

1294
02:04:39,200 --> 02:04:44,240
l am jealous, a little,
but not of you and Peter.

1295
02:04:44,400 --> 02:04:46,400
l'm....

1296
02:04:46,560 --> 02:04:49,760
l'm only feeling sorry
that l haven't anyone...

1297
02:04:49,960 --> 02:04:53,000
...with whom to discuss my feelings.

1298
02:04:53,160 --> 02:04:56,640
-Margot, l won't even--
-Listen, you've found a companionship...

1299
02:04:56,840 --> 02:04:58,560
...and l want you to enjoy it.

1300
02:04:58,760 --> 02:05:05,080
Only, in my heart, l feel l've got a
right to share feelings with someone too.

1301
02:05:05,680 --> 02:05:10,480
But l'm sure that Peter, that that boy,
he could never be that person for me.

1302
02:05:10,640 --> 02:05:12,160
[KNOCKING]

1303
02:05:12,360 --> 02:05:16,360
Maybe there's nothing
to be jealous about.

1304
02:05:16,520 --> 02:05:19,200
Maybe l'm just taking
the place of his cat.

1305
02:05:19,400 --> 02:05:24,760
-Will you please let me in my room?
ANNE: Just a minute, dear Mr. Dussel.

1306
02:05:35,560 --> 02:05:40,760
Well, here l go, to run the gauntlet.

1307
02:05:43,720 --> 02:05:46,080
Thank you so much.

1308
02:05:57,360 --> 02:05:59,680
Look at her.

1309
02:06:00,840 --> 02:06:04,560
A lot of good it did me to have a son.
l never see him.

1310
02:06:05,360 --> 02:06:08,080
Just a minute, dear.

1311
02:06:08,840 --> 02:06:12,680
l'd like to say a few words to my son.
Do you mind?

1312
02:06:12,920 --> 02:06:16,160
Peter, l do not want you staying up
till all hours tonight.

1313
02:06:16,320 --> 02:06:18,480
You need sleep.
You're a growing boy.

1314
02:06:18,680 --> 02:06:22,200
Annie won't stay late.
She's going to bed promptly at 9.

1315
02:06:22,400 --> 02:06:26,120
-Aren't you, Annie?
-Yes, Mother. May we go now?

1316
02:06:26,320 --> 02:06:28,440
Listen for the chimes, dear.

1317
02:06:48,400 --> 02:06:50,880
Aren't they impossible?

1318
02:06:52,120 --> 02:06:56,520
Treating us as if we're still
in the nursery.

1319
02:06:56,680 --> 02:07:00,840
Don't let it bother you.
It doesn't bother me.

1320
02:07:03,880 --> 02:07:07,400
l suppose you can't really blame them.

1321
02:07:07,600 --> 02:07:11,400
They think back
to what they were like at our age.

1322
02:07:11,600 --> 02:07:15,880
They don't realize
how much more advanced we are.

1323
02:07:26,400 --> 02:07:30,240
Already l know what l want to do,
don't you?

1324
02:07:30,400 --> 02:07:33,200
l want to be a journalist or something.

1325
02:07:33,360 --> 02:07:35,720
l love to write.

1326
02:07:36,760 --> 02:07:39,360
What do you want to do?

1327
02:07:40,800 --> 02:07:43,160
l know what l'd like right now.

1328
02:07:43,320 --> 02:07:46,720
l'd like to go to England and get
with the Free Dutch forces.

1329
02:07:46,880 --> 02:07:52,400
Peter, you wouldn't try a thing like that.
You'd never make it.

1330
02:07:52,600 --> 02:07:54,440
l'd make it.

1331
02:07:59,200 --> 02:08:03,160
Only a few of the hundreds that try do.

1332
02:08:03,800 --> 02:08:07,960
l know, but l'd like
to get in it and hit back.

1333
02:08:08,160 --> 02:08:12,120
To just sit here, it's not for me.

1334
02:08:16,640 --> 02:08:19,080
You like Margot, don't you?

1335
02:08:19,240 --> 02:08:21,400
Right from the start, you liked her.

1336
02:08:21,560 --> 02:08:24,320
Liked her better than me.

1337
02:08:26,120 --> 02:08:28,480
-l don't know.
-lt's all right.

1338
02:08:28,680 --> 02:08:33,040
Everyone feels that way.
Margot's so good.

1339
02:08:33,200 --> 02:08:37,920
She's sweet and bright and beautiful,
and l'm not.

1340
02:08:38,480 --> 02:08:41,680
-l wouldn't say that.
ANNE: Oh, no, l'm not.

1341
02:08:41,840 --> 02:08:46,120
l know that.
l know quite well that l'm not a beauty.

1342
02:08:46,320 --> 02:08:49,080
l never have been and never shall be.

1343
02:08:49,280 --> 02:08:52,080
l don't agree at all.

1344
02:08:53,040 --> 02:08:55,520
l think you're pretty.

1345
02:08:55,680 --> 02:08:57,760
That's not true.

1346
02:08:57,960 --> 02:09:00,200
And another thing.

1347
02:09:00,360 --> 02:09:04,560
You've changed. From the first, l mean.

1348
02:09:04,760 --> 02:09:07,800
l have?

1349
02:09:07,960 --> 02:09:11,960
l used to think
that you were awful noisy.

1350
02:09:13,320 --> 02:09:19,040
And what do you think now, Peter?
How have l changed?

1351
02:09:19,200 --> 02:09:20,880
Well.. .

1352
02:09:22,720 --> 02:09:24,960
.. .you're quieter.

1353
02:09:26,400 --> 02:09:29,200
l'm glad you don't just hate me.

1354
02:09:30,200 --> 02:09:32,680
l never said that.

1355
02:09:54,080 --> 02:09:58,960
l bet when you get out of here,
you'll never think of me again.

1356
02:09:59,120 --> 02:10:01,320
That's crazy.

1357
02:10:02,840 --> 02:10:07,000
When you get back with all your friends,
you're going to say:

1358
02:10:07,160 --> 02:10:11,040
''Now, what did l ever see
in that Miss Quack-Quack?''

1359
02:10:11,240 --> 02:10:15,400
-l haven't got any friends.
-Peter, of course you have.

1360
02:10:15,560 --> 02:10:19,800
-Everyone has friends.
-Not me.

1361
02:10:20,000 --> 02:10:24,680
l don't want any.
l get along fine without them.

1362
02:10:26,880 --> 02:10:30,720
Does that mean
you can get along without me too?

1363
02:10:32,160 --> 02:10:36,000
l think of myself as your friend.

1364
02:10:36,160 --> 02:10:38,760
No.

1365
02:10:38,920 --> 02:10:41,600
lf they were all like you...

1366
02:10:41,760 --> 02:10:43,920
...it'd be different.

1367
02:10:44,080 --> 02:10:48,080
[EXPLOSlONS IN DISTANCE]

1368
02:10:54,240 --> 02:10:56,240
Peter.. .

1369
02:10:57,720 --> 02:11:00,400
...did you ever kiss a girl?

1370
02:11:04,200 --> 02:11:05,680
Yes.

1371
02:11:05,880 --> 02:11:07,880
Once.

1372
02:11:08,960 --> 02:11:11,000
Was she pretty?

1373
02:11:11,160 --> 02:11:13,720
The girl you kissed?

1374
02:11:14,160 --> 02:11:16,760
l don't know. l was blindfolded.

1375
02:11:16,920 --> 02:11:20,200
lt was at a party.
One of those kissing games.

1376
02:11:21,480 --> 02:11:25,560
l don't suppose that really counts,
does it?

1377
02:11:26,920 --> 02:11:28,880
lt didn't with me.

1378
02:11:31,000 --> 02:11:34,040
l've been kissed twice.

1379
02:11:35,760 --> 02:11:38,920
Once, a man l'd never seen before
kissed me on the cheek...

1380
02:11:39,120 --> 02:11:41,800
...when he picked me up off the ice.

1381
02:11:42,000 --> 02:11:44,200
l was crying.

1382
02:11:45,920 --> 02:11:51,480
And the other was a friend
of Father's who kissed my hand.

1383
02:11:53,440 --> 02:11:56,680
You wouldn't say those counted,
would you?

1384
02:11:58,320 --> 02:12:00,960
l wouldn't say so.

1385
02:12:13,560 --> 02:12:17,480
l know, almost for certain,
Margot would never kiss anyone...

1386
02:12:17,640 --> 02:12:20,720
...unless she was engaged to them.

1387
02:12:23,440 --> 02:12:27,960
And l'm sure, too, that Mother
never touched a man before Father.

1388
02:12:30,240 --> 02:12:32,160
But l don't know.

1389
02:12:33,240 --> 02:12:35,920
Things are so different now.

1390
02:12:37,320 --> 02:12:39,520
What do you think?

1391
02:12:40,920 --> 02:12:47,160
Do you think a girl shouldn't kiss anyone
except if she's engaged or something?

1392
02:12:50,680 --> 02:12:54,680
lt's so hard to try
to think what to do.

1393
02:12:54,840 --> 02:12:59,920
Here we are with the whole world
falling around our ears...

1394
02:13:00,120 --> 02:13:02,760
...and you think...

1395
02:13:02,920 --> 02:13:07,400
...well, you don't know
what's going to happen tomorrow.

1396
02:13:09,960 --> 02:13:11,880
What do you think?

1397
02:13:14,920 --> 02:13:18,000
l suppose it depends on the girl.

1398
02:13:19,800 --> 02:13:24,560
With some,
no matter what they do, it's wrong.

1399
02:13:24,720 --> 02:13:26,600
But others.. .

1400
02:13:28,000 --> 02:13:30,600
.. .it wouldn't necessarily
be wrong with them.

